05414nam a22008175i 9780231546058DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018002557  a97802315460587 a10.7312/dore185222doi  a(DE-B1597)499063  a(OCoLC)1020295649  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY10aPS261 4aPS261 7aLIT0230002bisacsh04a813/.54099752231 aDore, Florence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNovel Sounds :bSouthern Fiction in the Age of Rock and Roll /cFlorence Dore. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b6 black and white images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: MINSTREL REALISM AT THE BIRTH OF ROCK -- t1. FUGITIVES AND FUTILITY: AGRARIAN BALLAD NOVELS IN BOB DYLAN’S MOMENT -- t2. NEW CRITICAL NOISE IN MUSIC CITY: THOMAS PYNCHON’S WILLIAM FAULKNER -- t3. THE BALLAD’S GENDER: FEMININITY AND INFORMATION IN GEORGIA -- t4. THE LEAD BELLY THING: WILLIAM STYRON’S RECORDS -- tCODA. NOBEL SOUNDS: BOB DYLAN’S NOVEL PRIZE -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tDiscography -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1950s witnessed both the birth of both rock and roll and the creation of Southern literature as we know it. Around the time that Chuck Berry and Elvis Presley put their electric spin on Southern vernacular ballads, a canonical group of white American authors native to rock’s birthplace began to write fiction about the electrification of those ballads, translating into literary form key cultural changes that gave rise to the infectious music coming out of their region. In Novel Sounds, Florence Dore tells the story of how these forms of expression became intertwined and shows how Southern writers turned to rock music and its technologies—tape, radio, vinyl—to develop the “rock novel.” Dore considers the work of Southern writers like William Faulkner, Flannery O’Connor, and William Styron alongside the music of Bessie Smith, Lead Belly, and Bob Dylan to uncover deep historical links between rock and Southern literature. Along with rock pioneers, Southern authors drew from blues, country, jazz, and other forms to create a new brand of realism that redefined the Southern vernacular as global, electric, and notably white. Resurrecting this Southern literary tradition at the birth of rock, Dore clarifies the surprising but unmistakable influence of rock and roll on the American novel. Along the way, she explains how literature came to resemble rock and roll, an anti-institutional art form if there ever was one, at the very moment academics claimed literature for the institution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictionzSouthern StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aRock music in literature. 0aRock musicxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aRock musiczSouthern StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Regional .2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/dore1852240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/is